<title type="html"><![CDATA[Munchausen Flash Cartridge progress]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6936&amp;p=75143#p75143"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />And it uses CF because SD's SPI is far slower than CF's parallel ATA without some hardware assistance.<br /></div><br />SD SPI mode is really slow because you need to do a write for every read. In native mode you don't need to do that, with the drawback that you can read only 4 bits at a time. I haven't tried reading SD cards on the NES - but I have on the SNES, and I can read files at upwards of 200 kB/s with good cards and some minimal hardware assistance (no DMA or anything, just a kind-of latch that combines two 4-bit data reads into a byte that gets placed on the bus at the next write). I'm not familiar enough with the ATA protocol to say which is faster or easier to implement.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=1181">mic_</a> — Sat Mar 05, 2011 1:32 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
